<div id="review_506586146" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/506586146" />
    <a title="Fred" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12320525-fred"><img alt="Fred" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1485447287p2/12320525.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/506586146?book_show_action=true">Jan 14, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Fred" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Fred" href="/user/show/12320525-fred">Fred</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12320525-fred?shelf=roth">roth</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer506586146" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1161409761242853338">This is not a great story it is four great stories. Roth plays with narrative offering several different resolutions for the same conflict. In the hands of a less skilled writer it might be confusing but it is never that way with Roth. Certain scenes -- many scenes -- are unforgettable. In the grand sweep of Roth&apos;s work this seems to be a transitional book. It is concerned with themes of identity and history. It is a complex narrative wrapped in four smaller intertwined stories and serves as a b</span>
  <span id="freeText1161409761242853338" style="display:none">This is not a great story it is four great stories. Roth plays with narrative offering several different resolutions for the same conflict. In the hands of a less skilled writer it might be confusing but it is never that way with Roth. Certain scenes -- many scenes -- are unforgettable. In the grand sweep of Roth's work this seems to be a transitional book. It is concerned with themes of identity and history. It is a complex narrative wrapped in four smaller intertwined stories and serves as a bridge between his shorter works and his larger most complex novels -- American Pastoral, Sabbath's Theater, I Married a Communist and Human Stain. There are places in The Counterlife that seem over-wrought, where the dialogue becomes diatribe. The point is made, the character developed, the narrative moves along, but one wonders if people really talk this way -- or write letters this way. Still it is a deeply engaging, creative story. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1161409761242853338" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

