<div id="review_140623874" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/140623874" />
    <a title="Frances Lockhart" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4727144-frances-lockhart"><img alt="Frances Lockhart" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1294977081p2/4727144.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/140623874?book_show_action=true">Jan 13, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Frances Lockhart" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Frances Lockhart" href="/user/show/4727144-frances-lockhart">Frances Lockhart</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer140623874" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17552101655873391602">My first Philip Roth experience and I&apos;m not overly impressed.<br/><br/>The idea of The Counterlife was a good one - alternate endings and outcomes to a person&apos;s life, kind of like an adult version of &quot;choose your own adventure&quot; stories I used to read as a kid. But the execution of this book was far too self involved, with pages and pages of monologues that seemed completely unrealistic (who has conversations where people woffle on for 20 minutes uninterupted??) and too heavy in the philosophical, zionisti</span>
  <span id="freeText17552101655873391602" style="display:none">My first Philip Roth experience and I'm not overly impressed.<br /><br />The idea of The Counterlife was a good one - alternate endings and outcomes to a person's life, kind of like an adult version of "choose your own adventure" stories I used to read as a kid. But the execution of this book was far too self involved, with pages and pages of monologues that seemed completely unrealistic (who has conversations where people woffle on for 20 minutes uninterupted??) and too heavy in the philosophical, zionistic, waxing lyrical about what a jew should do, should be, how they should live etc.<br /><br />I couldn't relate to any characters in this book. I read it for my bookclub and several members were unable/unwilling to finish it as it got quite boring. Nevertheless we all agreed Roth is clearly someone who CAN write, just didn't come across well in this novel.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17552101655873391602" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


