              <span id="reviewTextContainer76179209" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18163010631980896984">Amazingly well done. Wonderful on many levels.<br/><br/>1) Each of ~10 characters speaks a narrative in VERY different voice, showing a cool variety of viewpoints about several recurring topics. <br/><br/>2) Often the narrated events described are simply from a different viewpoint, but also sometimes reverse(!) with victim triumphant, betrayed victorious, deceased commemorating the (previous) survivor&apos;s funeral.<br/><br/>3) Sometimes includes amazingly well assembled expository essays, presented as monologues, by passionate,</span>
  <span id="freeText18163010631980896984" style="display:none">Amazingly well done. Wonderful on many levels.<br /><br />1) Each of ~10 characters speaks a narrative in VERY different voice, showing a cool variety of viewpoints about several recurring topics. <br /><br />2) Often the narrated events described are simply from a different viewpoint, but also sometimes reverse(!) with victim triumphant, betrayed victorious, deceased commemorating the (previous) survivor's funeral.<br /><br />3) Sometimes includes amazingly well assembled expository essays, presented as monologues, by passionate, thoughtful characters. In sequential chapters, quite opposite points of view are heard, but not necessarily in direct arguments. <br />The topics may be SPOILERS, so maybe skip over this list :<br />- health risks for sexual gain<br />- literary assaults on the author's family's privacy and even his theft of their autonomy<br />- modern western anti-semitism<br />- Jews' complex feelings about Zionism<br /><br />Since so much of Roth is a question about whether/how-much of Zuckerman's story is his own life, I looked up to find that he does have a brother (older than he) named Sandy Roth (who recently died).<br /><br />There's a study-group essay at <u>
  <b><a href="http://www.yiddishbookcenter.org/+10036" rel="nofollow noopener">this</a> </b>
</u>site. It spoils more than I do, but provide thought / discussion questions as well.<br /></span>
