<span id="freeTextContainer5078033693796675778">I can see how someone can not like this book. I can see how someone can dislike his work entirely. Although I consider myself a big fan and have read pretty much all he&apos;s ever published, I can see his flaws. <br/>He can be whiny, tiresome, repetitive and kind of cocky, and he&apos;s not as masterful a narrator as, say, mario vargas llosa. <br/>I wasn&apos;t even wild on his (widely considered) masterpiece, American pastoral. <br/>But I also know that everytime I pick up one of his books, there will be a chapter, a page </span>
  <span id="freeText5078033693796675778" style="display:none">I can see how someone can not like this book. I can see how someone can dislike his work entirely. Although I consider myself a big fan and have read pretty much all he's ever published, I can see his flaws. <br />He can be whiny, tiresome, repetitive and kind of cocky, and he's not as masterful a narrator as, say, mario vargas llosa. <br />I wasn't even wild on his (widely considered) masterpiece, American pastoral. <br />But I also know that everytime I pick up one of his books, there will be a chapter, a page or even a mere sentence that will just stop me dead. <br />And boy can he write a perfect sentence. <br />So au lieu de review, a short quote from this book. <br />"England's made a Jew of me in only eight weeks, which, on reflection, might be the least painful method. <br />A Jew without Jews, without Judaism, without Zionism, without Jewishness, without a temple or an army or even a pistol, a Jew clearly without a home, just the object itself, like a glass or an apple."</span>
